AB  - The racial identity of Finns has been ambiguous from a very early point in their history in the United States up to the present. One thing is certain: they were not conclusively white on arrival. The John Svan court case from 1908 is a reflection of the ways that an uncertain racial identity can be parlayed into a politicized agenda to deny citizenship rights to a particular group of immigrants, in this instance due to their radical political activities. A book commissioned by the Knights of Kaleva and published in 1957 by the Suomi Synod offers testimony that a half-century later, certain segments of the ethnic community remained concerned about their place in the nation's racial formation. And most recently, Alex Ross's 2007 article "Apparition in the Woods" reflects the persistence of the view that Finns are somehow racially different, though what it means in the twenty-first century for both people of Finnish ancestry and others is by no means clear. Adapted from the source document.
